&lt;p&gt;Additionally, this JSON configuration is suitable for different certificates in different environments based on matches for different URLs and hostnames.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Note: This option allows setting different SSL client certificates based on the URL or hostname. This option takes precedence over &amp;ndash;ssl-client-cert, &amp;ndash;ssl-client-key, and &amp;ndash;ssl-client-passphrase options. If there are no matching URLs in the list, these options will be used as fallback.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Trusted CA Certificates&lt;span class=&#34;hx:absolute hx:-mt-20&#34; id=&#34;trusted-ca-certificates&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;a href=&#34;#trusted-ca-certificates&#34; class=&#34;subheading-anchor&#34; aria-label=&#34;Permalink for this section&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Applicable when you need to trust custom CA certificates.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you don&amp;rsquo;t want to use the &amp;ndash;insecure option, you can provide additional trusted CA certificates like this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;--ssl-extra-ca-certs&lt;/code&gt;
Followed by a list of file paths to one or more PEM format trusted CA certificates.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
